Reviewed **`src/blog/people/drafts/Mira-Murati.md`** and appended a `FRESH EYES REVIEW` block at the bottom (no body edits). Light reality check confirmed the draft's most load-bearing claim — that Murati supplied the case against Altman via memos to the board — is real, so the "backstab reframe" is on solid ground.

**The two biggest issues I flagged:**

1. **The "builder" half of the core tension is underpaid.** The TL;DR and intro promise "the bridge versus the builder" and a woman who "ran the technology," but the body renders her almost entirely as a mediator. There's no concrete beat of her actual technical judgment, so "ran the technology" stays asserted rather than shown — a reader who knows AI will notice.

2. **The Sora "I'm actually not sure" moment is worked three times** (intro, empathy-turn reframe, closing re-quote). The first two earn it; the third callback has lost its charge.

The strongest thing in the draft — worth preserving — is the two empathy turns and the Swisher "feral… it's fine" / sworn "Not always" rhyme that shows the type's arc in her own words two years apart.

Sources for the reality check: [Forbes](https://www.forbes.com/sites/aliciapark/2026/05/06/ex-openai-cto-mira-murati-testifies-sam-altman-pit-openai-leaders-against-each-other-undermined-her/), [Gizmodo](https://gizmodo.com/ex-openai-cto-mira-murati-testifies-about-sam-altman-allegedly-lying-to-her-2000755394)
